      <h1>FICA Tax Explained: Social Security and Medicare</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>Jun 24, 2026</span><span>·</span><span>5 min read</span></div>
      <p class="article-intro">When you look at your US paycheck, FICA is one of the largest deductions. Here is what FICA tax pays for, how much you contribute, and how the annual caps work.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container" style="max-width:740px;">
    <div class="prose">
      <div class="callout"><strong>Quick math:</strong> Employees pay a flat 7.65% of their gross earnings for FICA taxes, and employers match that same amount. Self-employed individuals pay the full 15.3% themselves.</div>

      <h2>What is FICA tax?</h2>
      <p>FICA stands for the Federal Insurance Contributions Act. It is a mandatory federal payroll tax that funds two major social safety programs in the United States: Social Security (which provides retirement, disability, and survivor benefits) and Medicare (which provides health insurance for individuals aged 65 and older).</p>

      <h2>FICA tax breakdown: Where does your money go?</h2>
      <p>The standard FICA tax rate is divided into two separate components:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Social Security Tax:</strong> 6.2% of your gross wages. This money goes toward the federal Social Security trust funds.</li>
        <li><strong>Medicare Tax:</strong> 1.45% of your gross wages. This money goes toward funding Medicare hospital services.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Together, these two rates equal 7.65% for employees. For example, if you earn $1,000 gross in a pay period, $76.50 is deducted for FICA ($62.00 for Social Security and $14.50 for Medicare).</p>

      <h2>The Social Security wage base limit</h2>
      <p>The 6.2% Social Security tax does not apply to all your earnings if you are a high earner. The government sets an annual cap called the "wage base limit." For income earned beyond this limit, you stop paying the 6.2% Social Security tax for the rest of the year. The limit is adjusted annually for inflation.</p>
      <p>There is no wage base limit for the 1.45% Medicare tax. You continue to pay Medicare tax on every dollar of earnings, regardless of how much you make.</p>

      <h2>The Additional Medicare Tax</h2>
      <p>High earners are subject to an additional tax. If your earnings exceed $200,000 (for single filers) or $250,000 (for married couples filing jointly), an Additional Medicare Tax of 0.9% is applied to the amount exceeding the threshold. This brings your Medicare tax rate on those extra dollars to 2.35%.</p>

      <h2>Self-Employment Tax (SECA)</h2>
      <p>If you are a freelancer or business owner, you must pay the Self-Employment Contributions Act (SECA) tax. Since you are both the employer and employee, you are responsible for paying both shares, resulting in a flat 15.3% tax rate on your net self-employment earnings.</p>
